name: Artificial Intelligence for Computer Games
description: Examines the use of A.I. in computer games. Topics include general A.I. knowledge, path finding, movement, tactics and planning, strategy, state machines, learning, dialogue, and emotions.

name: Computational Structures in Computer Graphics
description: Studies the major topics in computer graphics: display and output technology, two and three dimensional manipulations; space curves and surfaces, hidden surface removal and shading models.

name: Human-Comp Interact
description: Topics related to interaction with technology, including interface design, software tools, 3-D interaction, virtual environments, interaction devices, collaboration, and visualization.
prerequisites: Prereq: COP 3530, and any one programming course (COP 2800, COP 3275, or COP 3229).

name: Research Mthd for Hcc
description: Introduces the fundamental methods and techniques to evaluate technologies and collect data from humans, including experimental design, types of variables, types of errors, hypothesis testing, survey design, behavioral and psychophysical methods.Â
prerequisites: Prereq: STA 3032, COT 3100, COP 3530, or equivalent.

name: Malware Rev Engr
description: Introducing the theory and practice of software reverse engineering applied to analysis of malicious software (malware). Students learn techniques of static and dynamic analysis to help identify the behavior of programs presented without documentation or source code and to identify possible remediation and avoidance techniques.
prerequisites: Prereq: CDA 3101 ; Coreq: COP 5615Â or consent of instructor.

name: Medical Image Analy
description: Image formation, reconstruction mathematics (Fourier slice theorem, Abel, Hankel and Radon transforms), PDE-based denoising and segmentation, multidimensional clustering algorithms, iso-surface extraction, basic differential geometry of curves and surfaces, multidimensional splines, active 2D/3D models, image matching/registration with application to multimodal co-registration.
prerequisites: Prereq: expertise in image proc./comp. vision, proficiency in C language or MATLAB.

name: Machine Learning
description: Concepts in developing computer programs that learn and improve with experience. Emphasis on methods based on probability, statistics, and optimization.

name: Advanced Data Science
description: Advanced topics in data science such as relational databases and parallel and distributed processing in the cloud, tree-based classifiers and support vector machines, dimensionality reduction and theories of visualization.

name: Embedded Systems
description: Design and verification of embedded systems including system level modeling/specification, design space exploration, hardware-software partitioning, architecture synthesis, compilation for area/power/performance code compression, real-time operating systems/databases, and functional validation of embedded systems.
prerequisites: Prereq: CDA 3101, COP 3530, and any one programming course (CGS 2414, CGS 3460, or CGS 3464).

name: Human-Computer Interaction
description: Studies the major topics in the study, planning and design of the interaction between people and computers. Topics include interface design (principles, theories and guidelines), virtual environments, interactive devices and collaboration.

name: User Experience Design
description: Introduces methods and tools used in User Experience Design (UXD): the early stages of software design focused on meeting user needs. Key concepts include user research, contextual design, design thinking, ideation, iterative design, prototyping, and design documentation. Projects utilize software tools used in the industry.

name: Computer and Information Science and Engineering Design 2
description: Involves completing a significant CEN-related project. Coordinate with the instructor and a project advisor, prepare a detailed technical report and deliver an oral presentation.

name: Software Test/Verifi
description: Concepts, principles, and methods for software testing and verification. Topics include human and machine-based testing strategies, formal proofs of correctness, and software reliability.

name: Information and Database Systems 1
description: First part of a two-course sequence that studies the essential concepts, principles and techniques of modern database systems. Topics include modeling and querying of data using conceptual data models as well as the development of a database application. (M)
prerequisites: Credits: 3; Prereq: COP 3504, or COP 3503 and COT 3100.

name: Individual Study in CISE
description: Problems in different areas of computer science.

name: Integrated Product and Process Design 2
description: Second part of a sequence where teams of engineering and business students partner with industry sponsors to design and build authentic products and processes.

name: Senior Project
description: Involves completing a significant CISE-related project. Coordinate with the instructor and a project advisor, prepare a detailed technical report and deliver an oral presentation. (M)
prerequisites: Prereq: senior CISE standing and approved project proposal.

name: Special Topics in CISE
description: Variable content provides an opportunity for in-depth study of topics not offered elsewhere and of topics of current significance.

name: Practical Work
description: One term practical software engineering work under industrial supervision as set forth in the Herbert Wertheim College of Engineering regulations. (S-U)

name: Co-Op Work in CISE
description: Practical engineering work under industrial supervision, as set forth in the Herbert Wertheim College of Engineering regulations. (S-U)

name: Comp and Info Sec
description: Covers systematic threat and risk assessment; programmed threats and controls in hardware, software, and human procedures; security policies, models, and mechanisms; theoretical limitations and practical implementations; certification and accreditation standards; and case study reviews. Coursework includes a significant term project.Â
prerequisites: Prereq: COP 4600 Operating Systems or equivalent

name: Intro to Cryptology
description: Introducing classical and modern cryptography and cryptanalysis, including symmetric and asymmetric (public key) ciphers. It covers cryptographic hash functions, block and stream ciphers, as well as differential and linear cryptanalysis. It reviews BAN logic, applications of cryptography, cryptographic standards and protocols, and analyzes case studies of failed implementations.
prerequisites: Prereq: COT 3100 Applications of Discrete Structures or equivalent ; Coreq: Â COT 5405Â Analysis of Algorithms or equivalent

name: Individual Study
prerequisites: Prereq: consent of faculty member supervising the study.

name: Graduate Seminar
description: Presentations by visiting researchers, faculty members, and graduate students.

name: Advanced Research
description: Research for doctoral students before admission to candidacy. Designed for students with a master's degree in the field of study or for students who have been accepted for a doctoral program. Not appropriate for students who have been admitted to candidacy.

name: Computer Network Fundamentals
description: Fundamental concepts, principles and standards of computer networks. Topics are introduced in bottom-up approach, starting from physical layer in OSI system architecture with a stronger focus on data link, mac, network and transport layers. (M)

name: Computer Networks
description: Design, implementation, and internals of networks. Routing, congestion control, internetworking, TCP/IP, optimization, and proxy services.

name: Programming Language Concepts
description: Introduces programming language principles, including language constructs, design goals, run-time structures, implementation techniques and exposure to a wide variety of programming paradigms.

name: Object-oriented Programming
description: Fundamental conceptual models for programming languages illustrated with specific programming languages and application problems. Specific topics include class and object models, inheritance among classes, objects and static and dynamic systems and implementations.

name: Operating Systems
description: Design and implementation of various components of a modern operating system, including I/O programming, interrupt handling, process and resource management, computer networks and distributed systems. (M)
prerequisites: Prereq: CDA 3101 and COP 3530; knowledge of C or C++ recommended.

name: Adv Data Structures
description: Development of efficient data structures used to obtain more efficient solutions to classical problems, such as those based on graph theoretical models, as well as problems that arise in application areas of contemporary interest.

name: Concurrent Program
description: Overview of principles and programming techniques. Reasoning about concurrency, synchronization, program structuring, multi-threaded server applications.

name: Data Base Manage Sys
description: Introduction to systems and procedures for managing large computerized databases.

name: Database Sys Implemen
description: DBMS architecture, query processing and optimization, transaction processing, index structures, parallel query processing, object-oriented and object-relational databases, and related topics.

name: Numerical Analysis: a Computational Approach
description: Numerical integration, nonlinear equations, linear and nonlinear systems of equations, differential equations and interpolation.
prerequisites: Prereq: COP 3504 or COP 3503 and MAS 3114.

name: Analys of Algorithms
description: Introduction and illustration of basic techniques for designing efficient algorithms and analyzing algorithm complexity.

name: Approx Algorithms
description: Fundamentals of algorithmic paradigms, analysis, techniques, and software. Topics include greedy methods, randomized algorithms, lP-rounding, approximability, covering, packing, clustering, and network problems.

name: Math Intelligent Sys
description: Mathematical methods commonly used to develop algorithms for computer systems that exhibit intelligent behavior.
prerequisites: Prereq: MAC 2313, Multivariate Calculus; MAS 3114 or MAS 4105, Linear Algebra; STA 4321, Mathematical Statistics.

name: Engineering Directed Independent Research
description: Provides firsthand, supervised research with a faculty advisor or postdoctoral or graduate student mentor. Projects may involve inquiry, design, investigation, scholarship, discovery or application. (S-U)

name: Prac/Intern/Coop Work
description: Practical cooperative engineering work under approved industrial and faculty supervision.

name: Engineering Grad Rsch
description: Course will provide the student with supervised research in a laboratory setting.

name: Special Topics in CISE
description: Variable content provides an opportunity for in-depth study of topics not offered elsewhere and of topics of current significance.

name: Engineering Economy
description: Basic principles and applications of economic decision-making between alternatives encountered in engineering systems projects. Analysis includes methodologies of economics and finance in addition to engineering fundamentals.
prerequisites: Prereq: MAC 2312 with a minimum grade of C.
